#########What is HPA?########
HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler) automatically increases or decreases the number of pods in a Kubernetes deployment depend on resource utilization such as CPU or Memory.

For example, if CPU utilization exceeds 70%, HPA automatically increases the number of pods. When utilization decreases, HPA removes extra pods.


##########How to Install HPA.#############
First, we ensured that Metrics Server was installed because HPA require metrics server.
Then, we configured CPU and Memory requests and limits in the manifest.

After that, we created an HPA with minimum and maximum replica counts and defined CPU and Memory utilization thresholds.

For example, if CPU utilization exceeds 70%, HPA automatically increases the number of pods. When utilization decreases, HPA removes extra pods.
		



“One HPA can target only one deployment. If We have 10 services, So It's depending on which services require autoscaling.  HPA is usually enabled only for high-traffic or resource-sensitive services.”

1 deployment = 1 HPA
not every service needs HPA.

